Group A: Short Questions (2 Marks)
1. Define the term ”Protocol” in the context of the Internet.
Protocol (Internet):
A protocol is a set of rules and standards that define how data is transmitted and received over the Internet between devices.
2. What is the primary difference between a Web Browser and a Search Engine?
Difference between Web Browser and Search Engine:
A web browser is software used to access and view web pages (e.g., Chrome, Firefox), whereas a search engine is a service that helps users find information on the web (e.g., Google, Bing).
3. Define the World Wide Web (WWW).
The World Wide Web is a collection of interconnected web pages and resources accessed through the Internet using web browsers.
4. Distinguish between a static web page and a dynamic web page.
	•	A static web page displays fixed content and does not change unless manually updated.
	•	A dynamic web page displays content that can change based on user interaction, time, or data from a server.

Group B: Long Questions (4 Marks)
5. Explain the client-server architecture of the web with a neat diagram.
Client–Server Architecture of the Web:

The client–server architecture is a model where clients (users’ computers or browsers) request services or resources, and servers provide those services or resources.
	•	The client (web browser) sends a request (HTTP/HTTPS) to the web server.
	•	The server processes the request, retrieves or generates the required web page.
	•	The server sends the response back to the client.
	•	The client displays the received web page to the user.
+---------+        Request (HTTP/HTTPS)        +-----------+
| Client  | --------------------------------> |   Server  |
| Browser |                                   | Web Server|
+---------+ <-------------------------------- +-----------+
             Response (Web Page / Data)
This architecture allows multiple clients to access services from a central server efficiently


6. Describe the functions of the following Internet services: Email, FTP, and VoIP.
Functions of Internet Services:
	1.	Email (Electronic Mail):
Email is used to send and receive electronic messages, documents, images, and other files over the Internet quickly and at low cost.
	2.	FTP (File Transfer Protocol):
FTP is used to upload and download files between a client and a server over the Internet.
	3.	VoIP (Voice over Internet Protocol):
VoIP allows users to make voice calls and video calls over the Internet instead of traditional telephone networks.

7. ”The Internet is a network of networks.” Elaborate on this statement explaining how
packet switching works.
The Internet is called a network of networks because it is formed by connecting many smaller networks (home networks, office networks, ISPs, and backbone networks) across the world. 
These networks are linked together using standard protocols so they can communicate with each other.
Packet Switching:
In packet switching, data is divided into small units called packets.
Each packet contains the destination address and travels independently through different routes across the network. Routers decide the best available path for each packet.
At the destination, all packets are reassembled in the correct order to form the original data. This method makes data transmission fast, efficient, and reliable.

Group C: Scenario-Based Questions (5 Marks)
8. A startup company wants to host a website that displays the same information to all
visitors and requires very low maintenance costs. However, they are being advised to use
a dynamic website. As a consultant, would you agree? Justify your answer.
No, I would not agree with the advice to use a dynamic website.
Since the startup’s website displays the same information to all visitors and requires very low maintenance cost, a static website is more suitable.
Static websites are simple, faster to load, more secure, cheaper to host, and do not require databases or server-side programming.
Dynamic websites are useful only when frequent updates, user interaction, or personalized content is needed, which is not required in this case.

9. A user types www.google.com into their browser, but the browser displays a ”Server Not
Found” error, even though the internet connection is active. However, accessing the site
via 142.250.190.46 works. Diagnose the problem and explain the underlying technology
that failed.
Diagnosis and Explanation:

The problem is due to a failure in DNS (Domain Name System) resolution.

When a user types www.google.com, the browser uses DNS to translate the domain name into its corresponding IP address.
Since accessing the website directly using the IP address 142.250.190.46 works, the web server and internet connection are functioning correctly.
However, the DNS server failed to resolve the domain name to the IP address, resulting in the “Server Not Found” error.

Underlying Technology Failed:
The Domain Name System (DNS), which acts like the Internet’s phonebook by converting human-readable domain names into machine-readable IP addresses.

10. A multinational corporation wants to share sensitive inventory data with specific suppliers
but does not want this information available to the general public. Explain which network
type (Intranet, Extranet, or Internet) they should implement and why.
Explanation:
An Extranet allows an organization to securely share selected internal information with authorized external users such as suppliers, partners, or vendors. 
It provides controlled access using authentication and security measures, ensuring that sensitive inventory data is not available to the general public, unlike the Internet. 
An Intranet is limited to internal employees only, while the Internet is public.
